A2 Milk & Natural Selection

Essential Question: How does genetics influence milk production and why do humans select for A2 milk?

Objective 2 →

What is A2 Milk?

A2 Milk: Milk containing only the A2 type of beta-casein protein, as opposed to regular milk which contains both A1 and A2 proteins.
Key fact 1 →
Key fact 2 →
Why it matters →

The Genetics of Beta-Casein

🧬 The CSN2 Gene

Located on Chromosome 6 in cattle

Controls beta-casein protein production

A1 Beta-Casein (Position 67):

Pro66 His67 Ile68

A2 Beta-Casein (Position 67):

Pro66 Pro67 Ile68
The mutation →

Inheritance of Milk Protein Types

Alleles:
A2 = Original allele (Proline at position 67)
A1 = Mutated allele (Histidine at position 67)
Possible Genotypes:
A2/A2 → Produces only A2 milk
A1/A2 → Produces both A1 and A2 milk
A1/A1 → Produces only A1 milk
Inheritance type →

Punnett Square: A2/A2 × A1/A2

Pure A2 cow × Hybrid cow

A2 A2
A1 A1/A2 A1/A2
A2 A2/A2 A2/A2
50% A2/A2 (Pure A2 milk)
50% A1/A2 (Mixed milk)

Punnett Square: A1/A2 × A1/A2

Hybrid cow × Hybrid cow

25% A1/A1 (Pure A1 milk)

Pattern recognition →

Natural vs Artificial Selection

Natural Selection: Environmental pressures determine survival
Artificial Selection: Humans choose which traits to breed
In this case →
The driver →

Why Do Humans Want A2 Milk?

BCM-7 (Beta-casomorphin-7): A peptide released during A1 milk digestion that may cause digestive discomfort in some people.
✅ Easier digestion for sensitive individuals
✅ No BCM-7 production
✅ Similar to human milk, goat, and sheep milk
Important notes →

Creating an A2 Herd

🐄 Breeding Strategy

How farmers convert their herds to A2

Step 1: Genetic testing of all cows (DNA from hair or blood)
Step 2: Identify A2/A2 cows and bulls
Step 3: Breed only A2/A2 animals together
Step 4: Gradually phase out A1 carriers
Practice Problem

If you start with 100 cows: 25 A1/A1, 50 A1/A2, 25 A2/A2

How many can produce pure A2 milk?

Click for answer →

Real-World Economics

💰 The Business of A2 Milk

Premium Price: A2 milk costs 50-100% more than regular milk
Testing Cost: $25-50 per cow for genetic testing
Conversion Time: 5-10 years to fully convert a herd
Market Growth: 15-20% annual growth globally
Bottom line →

A2 Genetics Around the World

🌍 Breed Distribution

High A2 Breeds: Guernsey (95%), Jersey (75%), Asian cattle (90%)
Mixed Breeds: Holstein (50%), Brown Swiss (65%)
Original cattle: All were A2/A2 (A1 is the mutation!)
Historical note →

Why is A2 milk an example of artificial selection?
The cows naturally prefer to produce A2
A2 cows survive better in nature
Humans select which cows to breed based on genetics
The environment causes the A2 mutation

Future of Genetic Selection in Agriculture

🔬 Beyond A2 Milk

Gene Editing: CRISPR technology could convert A1 to A2 genes
Other Proteins: Selection for lactose-free, hypoallergenic milk
Precision Breeding: DNA markers for multiple beneficial traits
Personalized Nutrition: Matching genetics to consumer needs
Think About It

If you were a dairy farmer, would you convert to A2? Why or why not?

Consider: costs, time, market demand, scientific evidence

🎯 KEY TAKEAWAYS

Genetics: A single SNP in the CSN2 gene determines A1 vs A2 milk
Inheritance: Codominant alleles follow Mendelian patterns
Punnett Squares: Predict offspring genotypes and milk types
Artificial Selection: Humans breed for desired traits (A2/A2)
Economics: Premium pricing drives selective breeding programs
Real-World Impact: Genetics affects agriculture, health, and consumer choice
